revision.text:
The '''All-night vigil''' is a service of the [[Eastern Orthodox Church]] (and Eastern Catholic Church) consisting of an aggregation of the three [[canonical hours]] of [[Vespers]], [[Matins]], and the [[First Hour]]. The vigil is celebrated on the eves of Sundays and of major liturgical feasts.<ref name="dunlop">{{cite book |last=Dunlop |first=Carolyn C. |title=Music of the Russian court chapel choir: 1796-1917 |year=2000 |publisher=Harwood Academihuic Publishers |isbn=978-90-5755-026-3 |edition= |location=Amsterdam |url=https://books.google.com/?id=UIM_K3a5XMMC&pg=RA2-PA80&lpg=RA2-PA80&dq=%22all+night+vigil%22+russian+orthodox#PRA2-PA58,M1 |pages=58‚Äì59}}</ref>
The [[vigil]] has been set to music most famously by [[Sergei Rachmaninoff]], whose [[All-Night Vigil (Rachmaninoff)|setting]] of selections from the service is one of his most admired works. [[Tchaikovsky]]'s [[All-Night Vigil (Tchaikovsky)|setting]] of the all-night vigil, along with his [[Liturgy of St. John Chrysostom (Tchaikovsky)|Divine Liturgy]] and his collection of nine sacred songs were of seminal importance in the later interest in Orthodox music in general, and settings of the all-night vigil in particular.{{sfn|''The Cambridge History of Russia''|2006|p=115}}{{sfn|Swain|2006|p=212}}{{sfn|Morozan|2013}} Other musical settings include those by [[Pavel Grigorievich Chesnokov|Chesnokov]], [[Alexander Gretchaninov|Grechaninov]], [[Mikhail Ippolitov-Ivanov|Ippolitov-Ivanov]], Alexander Kastalsky,<ref>{{cite book |last=Zvereva |first=Svetlana |title=Alexander Kastalsky: His Life and Music |year=2003 |publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd. |isbn=0-7546-0975-8 |edition= |location= |translator=Stuart Campbell |url=https://books.google.com/?id=6J7HvfHrRp0C&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73&dq=rachmaninoff+night+vigil+greatest+orthodox#PPA124,M1 |pages=124}}</ref> [[Hilarion Alfeyev]], [[Clive Strutt]] and [[Einojuhani Rautavaara]]. It is most often celebrated using a variety of traditional or simplified [[chant]] melodies based on the [[Octoechos]] or other sources.
==Order== When celebrated at the All-night vigil, the orders of Great Vespers and Matins vary somewhat from when they are celebrated by themselves.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biserica.org/Publicatii/ServiceBook/Gvespers.htm|title=The Order of Great Vespers|work=The Priest's Service Book|publisher=Diocese of the South|accessdate=2007-03-06| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070330103441/http://biserica.org/Publicatii/ServiceBook/Gvespers.htm| archivedate= 30 March 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://biserica.org/Publicatii/ServiceBook/Smatins.htm|title=The Order of Matins on Sundays and Feast Days|work=The Priest's Service Book|publisher=Diocese of the South|accessdate=2007-03-06}}</ref> In parish usage, many portions of the service such as the readings from the Synaxarion during the Canon at Matins are abbreviated or omitted, and it therefore takes approximately two or two and a half hours to perform.
The Psalms cited below are numbered according to the [[Septuagint]], which differs from that found in the [[Masoretic]].
===Great Vespers=== * Great [[incense|Censing]] of the entire church, done in silence * Opening exclamation by the priest: "Glory to the holy, consubstantial, life-creating, and undivided [[Trinity]], always, now and ever, and unto ages of ages" * "Come let us worship God our king" * "Psalm of creation", [[Psalm 104|Psalm 103]], sung (in modern practise only selected verses) * Great Litany * First [[Kathisma]] (entirely on Sundays) or the 1st stasis on weekdays * [[Little Litany]] * "Lord I have cried" (psalms 140,141,129, 116), with appointed [[sticheron|stichera]], ending with the ''Dogmatic [[Theotokion]]'', a hymn addressed to the [[Theotokos]] * [[Entrance (Liturgical)|Entrance]] *''[[Phos Hilaron]]'' ("O gladsome light") * [[Prokeimenon]] for the day * [[Old Testament]] readings (if appointed) * Augmented Litany * The prayer, "Vouchsafe, O Lord" * Litany of Askings * [[Lity (Orthodox Vespers)|Litia]] (on Sundays and certain feastdays) * Aposticha * [[Nunc dimittis]] ("Now lettest Thou thy servant depart in peace") and [[Trisagion]] prayers * [[Troparion|Apolytikion]]‚Äîon Sundays: "Rejoice, O Virgin Theotokos..."; otherwise, the one appointed for the feast * [[Artoklasia]], if there was a Litia * "Blessed be the name of the Lord", Psalm 33 (first ten verses), and a [[blessing]]
===Matins=== * "Glory to God in the highest", "O Lord, open Thou my lips" * Six Psalms (Psalms 3, 37, 61, 87, 102, and 142) * Great Litany * "God is the Lord", with verses from Psalm 117 * [[Apolytikion]]‚Äîon Sundays: from the [[Octoechos (liturgy)|Octoechos]]; otherwise, for the feast‚Äîand its appropriate Theotokion * Kathisma * Little Litany * Sessional hymns * Kathisma * Little Litany * Sessional hymns * 17th Kathisma ([[Psalm 119|Psalm 118]]) or [[Polyeleon]] (Psalms 134 and 135) as appointed for the season * [[Megalynarion]] (feast days) * Resurrectional Troparia, "The Angelic Council..." (Sundays only) * Little Litany * [[Anabathmoi]] * [[Hypakoe]] * Matins Prokeimenon * [[Matins Gospel]] * "Having beheld the Resurrection of Christ" (on Sundays), or the appointed stichera (on feast days) *[[Psalm 51|Psalm 50]] ("Have mercy on me, O God", ''Miserere'') * Prayer, "O God save thy people and bless thine inheritance..." * [[Canon (hymnography)|Canon]]. The people venerate the [[Gospel Book]] if it is Sunday, or the [[icon]] of the feast if it is a weekday * "Holy is the Lord our God" (Sundays only) * Little Litany * [[Exapostilarion]] * [[Lauds|Praises]] (Psalms 148 to 150, with stichera) * [[Gloria in Excelsis Deo|Great Doxology]] ("Glory to God in the highest") * Appointed troparia * Augmented Litany * Litany of Askings * [[Dismissal (liturgy)|Dismissal]] * [[Polychronion]] * [[First Hour]]
