{{Italic title}} {{taxobox |image = Faidherbia albida.JPG |image_caption = ''F. albida'' growing with [[Arecaceae|palms]] and [[maize]] crops |regnum = [[Plant]]ae |unranked_divisio = [[Angiosperms]] |unranked_classis = [[Eudicots]] |unranked_ordo = [[Rosids]] |ordo = [[Fabales]] |familia = [[Fabaceae]] | subfamilia = [[Caesalpinioideae]]<ref name="6subfamilies">{{cite journal | author = '''The Legume Phylogeny Working Group (LPWG).''' | year = 2017 | title = A new subfamily classification of the Leguminosae based on a taxonomically comprehensive phylogeny | journal = [[Taxon (journal)|Taxon]] | volume = 66 | issue = 1 | pages = 44‚Äì77 | url = http://www.ingentaconnect.com/contentone/iapt/tax/2017/00000066/00000001/art00004 | doi = 10.12705/661.3}}</ref> | unranked_tribus = [[Mimosoideae|Mimosoid clade]]<ref name="6subfamilies"/> |genus = '''''Faidherbia''''' |genus_authority = [[Auguste Chevalier|A.Chev.]] |species = '''''F. albida''''' |binomial = ''Faidherbia albida'' |binomial_authority = ([[Delile]]) [[A.Chev.]] |range_map = Faidherbia alba Distribution Map.svg |range_map_caption = The range of ''Faidherbia albida''. }} [[File:Faidherbia albida_fleur_MHNT.jpg|thumb|''Faidherbia albida'' - [[MHNT]]]]
'''''Faidherbia''''' is a genus of [[Fabaceae|leguminous]] plants containing one species, '''''Faidherbia albida''''', native to [[Africa]] and the [[Middle East]]. The species was formerly widely included in the genus ''[[Acacia]]'' as ''Acacia albida''. It has also been introduced to [[Pakistan]] and [[India]]. Common names for it include '''apple-ring acacia''' (their circular, indehiscent seed pods resemble apple rings),<ref name=wpa1>{{cite web |last1=Armstrong |first1=W. P. |title=Unforgettable Acacias, A Large Genus Of Trees & Shrubs |url=http://waynesword.palomar.edu/plaug99.htm |website=Wayne's Word |accessdate=17 November 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110064020/http://waynesword.palomar.edu/plaug99.htm |archivedate=10 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> '''ana tree''', '''balanzan tree''', '''gao tree'''<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/16/regreening-niger-how-magical-gaos-transformed-land</ref> and '''winter thorn'''.<ref name="ILDIS">[http://www.ildis.org/LegumeWeb?sciname=Faidherbia+albida ILDIS LegumeWeb]</ref>
It is a thorny [[tree]] growing up {{convert|6‚Äì30|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall and {{convert|2|m|ft|abbr=on}} in trunk diameter. Its deep-penetrating [[tap root]] makes it highly resistant to drought. The bark is grey, and fissured when old. There are 11,000 seeds/kg. ''Faidherbia albida'' is not listed as being a [[threatened species]].<ref name="ILDIS"/><ref name=apd>African Plants Database: [http://www.ville-ge.ch/cjb/bd/africa/details.php?langue=an&id=62154 ''Faidherbia albida''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926230106/http://www.ville-ge.ch/cjb/bd/africa/details.php?langue=an&id=62154 |date=2007-09-26 }}</ref><ref name="fao">FAO: [http://www.fao.org/docrep/006/Q2190E/Q2190E10.htm Handbook on Seeds of Dry-Zone Acacias]</ref>
It grows in areas with {{convert|250‚Äì600|mm|in|abbr=on}} of rain per year.<ref name="fao"/>
''Faiderbia albida'' is known in the [[Bambara language]] as ''balanzan'' and is the official tree of the city of [[Segou]] on the [[Niger River]] in central [[Mali]]. According to legend, Segou is home to 4,444 ''balanzan'' trees, plus one mysterious "missing tree" the location of which cannot be identified.
In [[Serer language|Serer]] and some of the [[Cangin languages]], it is called ''Saas''. [[Serer creation myth#Saas|Saas]] figures prominently in the [[Serer creation myth|creation myth of the Serer people]]. According to their [[creation myth]], it is the [[tree of life]] and fertility.<ref name="Serer civilisation">{{fr icon}} [[Henry Gravrand|Gravrand, Henry]], "La civilisation [[Serer people|sereer]]", vol. II : Pangool, Nouvelles √©ditions africaines, [[Dakar]], 1990, pp. 125‚Äì127, {{ISBN|2-7236-1055-1}}</ref>
The northernmost natural populations are found in [[relict]] groves in [[Israel]] (in the [[Shimron]] nature reserve, near the [[community settlement (Israel)|community settlement]] of [[Timrat]]). All of the trees in a given grove are genetically identical and seem to have multiplied by [[vegetative reproduction]] only, for thousands of years.{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}
==Cultivation and uses== ''Faidherbia albida'' is important in the [[Sahel]] for raising [[bee]]s, since its flowers provide bee [[Forage (honeybee)|forage]] at the close of the rainy season, when most other local plants do not.<ref name="world">[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928031700/http://www.worldagroforestry.org/Sites/TreeDBS/aft/speciesPrinterFriendly.asp?Id=1 World AgroForestry]</ref>
The seed pods are important for raising [[livestock]], are used as [[camel]] [[fodder]] in [[Nigeria]],<ref name="world"/> and are relished by elephant, antelope, buffalo, baboons and various browsers and grazers, though strangely ignored by warthog and zebra.<ref>{{cite journal | journal = Journal of Tropical Ecology | volume = 6 | issue = 04 | date = 1990 | pages = 445‚Äì457 | title = Fruit production by Acacia albida trees in Zambezi riverine woodlands | author = Kevin M. Dunham | doi = 10.1017/S0266467400004843}}</ref>
The wood is used for canoes, mortars, and pestles and the bark is pounded in Nigeria and used as a packing material on pack animals. The wood has a density of about 560&nbsp;kg/m<sup>3</sup> at a water content of 12%.<ref name="fao2">FAO: [http://www.fao.org/docrep/V5360E/v5360e0f.htm Role of acacia species in the rural economy of dry Africa and the Near East]</ref> The energy value of the wood as fuel is 19.741 kJ/kg.<ref name="world"/>
Ashes of the wood are used in making soap and as a depilatory and tanning agent for hides. The wood is used for carving; the thorny branches useful for a natural barbed fence.<ref>VITA (1977) {{full citation needed|date=March 2016}}</ref> Pods and foliage are highly regarded as livestock fodder. Some 90% of Senegalese farmers interviewed by Felker (1981) collected, stored, and rationed Acacia alba pods to livestock. Zimbabweans use the pods to stupefy fish. Humans eat the boiled seeds in times of scarcity in Zimbabwe.
It is also used for [[nitrogen fixation]], [[erosion control]] for crops, for food, drink and medicine. Unlike most other trees, it sheds its leaves in the rainy season; for this reason, it is highly valued in [[agroforestry]] as it can grow among field crops without shading them.<ref name="ILDIS"/> The leaves from this legume tree are high in nitrogen, and can double yields in maize crops when added to the soil.<ref name="Evergreen Agriculture">http://www.evergreenagriculture.net/sites/default/files/Evergreen%20Agriculture%20Garrity%20et%20al%20Food%20Security.pdf</ref>
=== Medicinal uses === The extract is used to treat ocular infections in [[farm]] animals.<ref name="world"/>
