The 2000 census reported 27,839 residents of [[Switzerland]] self-identifying as [[Hindu]]s (0.38% of the total population; 1.11% in [[Berne]], 1% in [[Zurich]], 0.27% in Geneva). Most of them are [[Sri Lankan Tamils]] (81.2%). Approximately 90% of Hindu adherents are foreign-born,<ref>[http://www.religionenschweiz.ch/hinduismus.html Hinduismus in der Schweiz] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710180337/http://www.religionenschweiz.ch/hinduismus.html |date=2015-07-10 }}</ref> and about a third of them have the status of refugee or asylum seeker. The [[Sri Sivasubramaniar Temple]], located in the [[Sihl Valley]] in [[Adliswil]], is the most famous and largest [[Hindu temple]] in Switzerland,<ref name="religionenschweiz">[http://www.religionenschweiz.ch/hinduismus.html Religionen in der Schweiz: Hinduismus] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710180337/http://www.religionenschweiz.ch/hinduismus.html |date=2015-07-10 }}</ref> the [[Arulmihu Sivan Temple]] located in Glattbrugg is dedicated to [[Shiva]],<ref name="zul-20120702">{{cite web|url=http://www.zuonline.ch/artikel_72063.html|title=Umzug zu Ehren der G√∂tter|publisher=[[Z√ºrcher Unterl√§nder]]|author=Simone Thommen Awe|language=German|date=2012-07-02|accessdate=2015-03-20|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402123751/http://www.zuonline.ch/artikel_72063.html|archivedate=2015-04-02|df=}}</ref> and the latest foundation is the [[Sri Vishnu Thurkkai Amman Temple]] in D√ºrnten in 2010.<ref name="zol-20130720">{{cite web|url=http://www.zol.ch/bezirk-hinwil/duernten/Ein-Pfauentanz-fuer-Goettin-Amman/story/30175702|title=Ein Pfauentanz f√ºr G√∂ttin Amman|publisher=[[Z√ºrcher Oberl√§nder]]|author=Regula Lienin|language=German|date=2013-07-20|accessdate=2014-12-18}}</ref><ref name="lz-20100117">{{cite web|url=http://www.aargauerzeitung.ch/schweiz/indische-handwerker-bauen-hindu-tempel-ohne-bewilligung-5842098|title=Indische Handwerker bauen Hindu-Tempel ‚Äì ohne Bewilligung|publisher=[[Limmattaler Zeitung]]|author=Patrizia Legnini|language=German|date=2010-01-17|accessdate=2014-12-18}}</ref>

In earlier censuses, Hinduism figured together with other non-Abrahamic traditions (mainly [[Buddhism]]) as "other churches and communities". These accounted for 0.12% in 1970, 0.19% in 1980, 0.42% in 1990 and 0.78% in 2000 (0.38% Hinduism, 0.29% Buddhism, 0.11% other). Hinduism overtook Judaism as the third largest religion in Switzerland (after Christianity and Islam) during the 1990s and was tied at 0.38% with the [[New Apostolic Church]] in 2000.

