In [[Scandinavian folklore]], a '''r√•''' {{sv}}, is a keeper or warden of a particular location or landform. The different species of r√• are sometimes distinguished according to the different spheres of nature with which they were connected, such as ''[[skogsr√•]]''<ref>{{cite book|last=Granberg|first=Gunnar|title=Skogsr√•et i yngre nordisk folktradition|series=Skrifter / utg. av Kungl. Gustav Adolfs akademien f√∂r folklivsforskning, 99-0440828-9 ; 3|date=1935|publisher=Lundequistska bokh.|location=Uppsala|language=Swedish|id={{LIBRIS|321677}}}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Hultkrantz|editor-first=√Öke|title=The supernatural owners of nature: Nordic symposion on the religious conceptions of ruling spirits (genii loci, genii speciei) and allied concepts|series=Stockholm studies in comparative religion, 0562-1070 ; 1|date=1961|publisher=Almqvist & Wiksell|location=Stockholm|id={{LIBRIS|541848}}}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=H√§ll|first=Mikael|title=Skogsr√•et, n√§cken och dj√§vulen: erotiska naturv√§sen och demonisk sexualitet i 1600- och 1700-talens Sverige|date=2013|publisher=Mal√∂rt|location=Stockholm|language=Swedish|isbn=978-91-978751-2-7|id={{LIBRIS|13887591}}}}</ref> or ''[[huldra]]'' (forest), ''[[sj√∂r√•]]''<ref>Nationalencyklopedin, multimedia plus, 2000</ref> (freshwater) or ''havsr√•'' (saltwater), and ''[[bergsr√•]]''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Grimberg|first1=Carl|last2=√Öberg|first2=Alf|title=Svenska folkets underbara √∂den. 4, 1660‚Äì1707|date=1960|location=Stockholm|id={{LIBRIS|8074835}}}}</ref> (mountains).
In accordance with old belief, all objects, animals and plants had its own ''r√•'' or spirit which protected them. A ''r√•'' could also have power over areas and phenomena belonging to humans, such as the ''skeppsr√•et'' (r√• of the ship) and the ''gruvr√•et'' (r√• of the mine). The r√• was not only known in the Nordic culture, but was also known in the Sami culture, where it was called ''radie''. Though the specific ''R√•'''s, such as the ''skogsr√•'' and the ''bergsr√•'', was normally defined as feminine, the species ''r√•'' as such could be both masculine and feminine. It was important for humans to cultivate a good relationship to them, as it had power over the nature forces and animals belonging to them, and could cause humans who interfered with them both luck and the opposite.
