'''Suhag Raat''' (Hindi: ‡§∏‡•Å‡§π‡§æ‡§ó ‡§∞‡§æ‡§§, {{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|ÿ≥€Åÿß⁄Ø ÿ±ÿßÿ™}}}}, {{lang-bn|‡¶´‡ßÅ‡¶≤‡¶∂‡¶Ø‡ßç‡¶Ø‡¶æ}}), a significant ritual in the life of a newlywed couple in the [[Indian subcontinent]], refers to the first night when the marriage is [[Consummation|consummated]]. Prior to then, both the bride and bridegroom are assumed to be virgins. The bed of the newlywed couple is decorated with flowers, which are believed to bring sweetness to their relationship.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hindu Wedding|url=http://www.hinduwedding.info/marriage-ceremony.html|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> This is an important custom followed in [[Marriage in Hinduism|Vedic Hindu marriages]]. The tradition also extends to [[Jainism|Jains]], [[Buddhism]], and [[Muslims]]. In some areas, especially in eastern India, "Suhag Raat" is also referred to as "Fourth Night" because this ritual is observed on the fourth night of [[Oriya Hindu wedding|marriage]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Oriya Wedding|url=http://www.culturalindia.net/weddings/regional-weddings/oriya-wedding.html|accessdate=1 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bengali Wedding|url=http://www.gingerevents.com/weddings/traditional_weddings/bengali_wedding.html|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> of the wedding.

==Custom==
The female members of the bridegroom's family customarily guide the bride to the decorated bedroom where she waits for her husband's arrival{{mdash}}optionally, with a glass of milk.
<ref>{{cite web|title=Rituals and Customs of first night in Hindu Marriage|url=http://marriage.sudesh-kumar.com/2009/05/first-night-in-hindu-marriage.html|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rituals of Suhag Raat|url=http://www.speakingtree.in/spiritual-slideshow/seekers/faith-and-rituals/rituals-of-suhagraat/217948|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Importance of Milk in Suhag Raat|url=http://www.factsvita.com/top-10-facts-behind-serving-milk-suhagraat-wedding-night|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> The couple's bed is decorated with [[rose]]s, [[jasmine]] and [[Polianthes tuberosa|rajnigandha]] flowers. It is traditional for the groom to wait outside with the relatives and family for some time before he joins the bride in the decorated bedroom. The bride supposedly waits for her husband behind a veil ("[[ghoonghat]]"). The husband slowly takes the veil off to reveal the bride's face in a ritual called "Muh Dekhai" i.e. showing of bride's face.<ref>{{cite web|title=Importance of Suhag Raat|url=http://www.exoticindiaart.com/product/paintings/first-time-suhag-raat-MF18|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> After consummation, the wife is also known as "Ardhangini" in Hindu Philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wedding Night customs or Suhag Raat|url=http://www.freeindianmatrimony.com/blog/Wedding-night-customs-or-Suhagraat.html|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Suhag Raat Customs|url=http://www.bollywoodshaadis.com/articles/suhagrat-customs--a-night-to-remember-995|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> It is customary that the couple wakes up early next morning before anyone else, bathe, and change their clothing. The clothing worn the previous night is considered dirty, so the [[dhobi]] customarily arrives the next morning to collect them for cleaning. The Suhag Raat may extend to a honeymoon tour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Suhag Raat|url=https://bollywoodinbritain.wordpress.com/tag/suhaag-raat|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref>

